00:51:06,820 --> 00:51:10,820
But the important thing is,

1096
00:51:10,820 --> 00:51:12,820
if you work out all

1097
00:51:12,820 --> 00:51:14,820
of the details of the vacuum,

1098
00:51:14,820 --> 00:51:16,820
if you work out all

1099
00:51:16,820 --> 00:51:18,820
of the details of the equations,

1100
00:51:18,820 --> 00:51:22,820
you will also find, in that case,

1101
00:51:22,820 --> 00:51:25,820
that it behaves like a magnetic field.

1102
00:51:25,820 --> 00:51:27,820
F. F is kind of like

1103
00:51:27,820 --> 00:51:29,820
a component of a magnetic field.

1104
00:51:29,820 --> 00:51:34,820
And it has the effect of splitting the masses

1105
00:51:34,820 --> 00:51:37,820
of the different particles which rotate into each other

1106
00:51:37,820 --> 00:51:40,820
under the supersymmetry transformation.

1107
00:51:40,820 --> 00:51:42,820
Which of the particles which rotate into each other

1108
00:51:42,820 --> 00:51:44,820
under the supersymmetry transformation?

1109
00:51:44,820 --> 00:51:47,820
The fermions and the bosons.

1110
00:51:47,820 --> 00:51:52,820
So, the main lesson to draw from this

1111
00:51:52,820 --> 00:51:59,820
is that there is a theory of supersymmetry breaking

1112
00:51:59,820 --> 00:52:02,820
which is very close in spirit

1113
00:52:02,820 --> 00:52:04,820
to spontaneous symmetry breaking,

1114
00:52:04,820 --> 00:52:08,820
to conventional spontaneous symmetry breaking.

1115
00:52:08,820 --> 00:52:11,820
It does not require the equations to be not supersymmetric.

1116
00:52:11,820 --> 00:52:14,820
It requires the solutions of the equations

1117
00:52:14,820 --> 00:52:18,820
to somehow be non-symmetric

1118
00:52:18,820 --> 00:52:20,820
with respect to the supersymmetry.

1119
00:52:20,820 --> 00:52:23,820
And the result is, just like in the magnet,

1120
00:52:23,820 --> 00:52:26,820
the atom and the magnet will have split levels

1121
00:52:26,820 --> 00:52:29,820
in the same way the analog

1122
00:52:29,820 --> 00:52:32,820
of the atom and the magnet

1123
00:52:32,820 --> 00:52:35,820
would be a fermion or a boson, a particle,

1124
00:52:35,820 --> 00:52:37,820
and the two things which

1125
00:52:37,820 --> 00:52:39,820
are interchanged by the supersymmetry

1126
00:52:39,820 --> 00:52:41,820
will have their energies split.

1127
00:52:41,820 --> 00:52:43,820
The fermions and the bosons.

1128
00:52:43,820 --> 00:52:46,820
That's the implication of all of this.

1129
00:52:46,820 --> 00:52:49,820
One more implication.

1130
00:52:49,820 --> 00:52:54,820
If the vacuum is not supersymmetric,

1131
00:52:54,820 --> 00:52:57,820
if the vacuum is not supersymmetric,

1132
00:52:57,820 --> 00:52:59,820
the simple implication of that,

1133
00:52:59,820 --> 00:53:01,320
just in the same way if

1134
00:53:01,320 --> 00:53:02,820
the vacuum is not rotationally symmetric,

1135
00:53:02,820 --> 00:53:05,820
then a rotation of the vacuum gives you something new.

1136
00:53:05,820 --> 00:53:08,820
It gives you something which is not the vacuum.

1137
00:53:08,820 --> 00:53:10,820
It gives you a goldstone boson.

1138
00:53:10,820 --> 00:53:12,820
What happens if

1139
00:53:12,820 --> 00:53:15,820
the vacuum of supersymmetry transformation

1140
00:53:15,820 --> 00:53:19,820
is not symmetric under supersymmetry?

1141
00:53:19,820 --> 00:53:22,820
Then a supersymmetry transformation on the vacuum

1142
00:53:22,820 --> 00:53:24,820
gives you something new.

1143
00:53:24,820 --> 00:53:27,820
Anybody want to guess what that something new is?

1144
00:53:30,820 --> 00:53:33,820
Well, remember that supersymmetry transformations

1145
00:53:33,820 --> 00:53:36,820
interchange bosons and fermions.

1146
00:53:36,820 --> 00:53:41,820
The vacuum is formally counted as a boson state.

1147
00:53:42,820 --> 00:53:46,820
It's formally counted as a boson state.

1148
00:53:46,820 --> 00:53:49,820
But whatever the vacuum is,

1149
00:53:49,820 --> 00:53:53,820
a rotation by a supersymmetry transformation

1150
00:53:53,820 --> 00:53:57,820
will change it by adding a fermion.

1151
00:53:57,820 --> 00:54:00,820
A supersymmetry transformation always takes,

1152
00:54:00,820 --> 00:54:04,820
always adds or subtracts a fermion.

1153
00:54:04,820 --> 00:54:06,820
So the result is

1154
00:54:06,820 --> 00:54:08,820
that whenever supersymmetry is

1155
00:54:08,820 --> 00:54:10,820
spontaneously broken in this way,

1156
00:54:10,820 --> 00:54:14,820
there is a massless particle.

1157
00:54:14,820 --> 00:54:17,320
And the massless particle is

1158
00:54:17,320 --> 00:54:19,820
a fermion instead of a boson.

1159
00:54:19,820 --> 00:54:21,820
It's what happens to the vacuum

1160
00:54:21,820 --> 00:54:24,820
when you do the supersymmetry transformation.

1161
00:54:24,820 --> 00:54:27,820
If the vacuum is symmetric,

1162
00:54:27,820 --> 00:54:29,820
then you don't get anything new.

1163
00:54:29,820 --> 00:54:32,820
If the vacuum is not symmetric under supersymmetry,

1164
00:54:32,820 --> 00:54:35,820
which means that this is not equal to zero,

1165
00:54:35,820 --> 00:54:37,820
then when you do a supersymmetry transformation,

1166
00:54:37,820 --> 00:54:38,820
you do get something new,

1167
00:54:38,820 --> 00:54:42,820
and that new thing is a massless fermion.

1168
00:54:42,820 --> 00:54:44,820
It has a name.

1169
00:54:44,820 --> 00:54:47,820
Sometimes it's called the goldstone fermion

1170
00:54:47,820 --> 00:54:49,820
instead of a goldstone boson,

1171
00:54:49,820 --> 00:54:51,820
if that makes sense.

1172
00:54:51,820 --> 00:54:54,820
And sometimes it's called a goldstino.

1173
00:54:54,820 --> 00:54:57,820
Eno usually refers to a fermion.

1174
00:54:57,820 --> 00:55:02,820
The goldstino or the goldstone boson

1175
00:55:08,820 --> 00:55:11,820
is the particle that's generated

1176
00:55:11,820 --> 00:55:14,820
by doing a small supersymmetry transformation on the vacuum

1177
00:55:14,820 --> 00:55:16,820
if the vacuum is not symmetric.

1178
00:55:16,820 --> 00:55:20,820
So the two consequences

1179
00:55:20,820 --> 00:55:24,820
of spontaneous supersymmetry breaking,

1180
00:55:24,820 --> 00:55:25,820
there are two of them.

1181
00:55:25,820 --> 00:55:29,820
One is that the vacuum energy is not zero.

1182
00:55:29,820 --> 00:55:35,820
The minimum is not when v is equal to zero.

1183
00:55:35,820 --> 00:55:37,820
Or...

1184
00:55:38,820 --> 00:55:41,820
That's one.

1185
00:55:41,820 --> 00:55:43,820
So the vacuum energy is not equal to zero.

1186
00:55:43,820 --> 00:55:45,820
And the other consequence is

1187
00:55:45,820 --> 00:55:47,820
that there's a massless fermion,

1188
00:55:47,820 --> 00:55:49,820
a new massless fermion,

1189
00:55:49,820 --> 00:55:53,820
unexpected and as...

1190
00:55:53,820 --> 00:55:57,820
as unexpected as a goldstone boson.

1191
00:55:57,820 --> 00:55:59,820
And they're for the same reasons,

1192
00:55:59,820 --> 00:56:01,820
that the supersymmetry transformation

1193
00:56:01,820 --> 00:56:02,820
acting on the whole world

1194
00:56:02,820 --> 00:56:04,820
has to give you a new state,

1195
00:56:04,820 --> 00:56:07,820
and that new state is called the goldstone fermion.

1196
00:56:07,820 --> 00:56:08,820
Okay.

1197
00:56:08,820 --> 00:56:12,820
That's spontaneous supersymmetry breaking in a nutshell.

1198
00:56:12,820 --> 00:56:14,820
One more...

1199
00:56:14,820 --> 00:56:16,820
Well, there are two more points.

1200
00:56:16,820 --> 00:56:17,820
I mean, I'm giving you some...

1201
00:56:17,820 --> 00:56:19,820
I want to give you some jargon now

1202
00:56:19,820 --> 00:56:23,820
so that you'll recognize the jargon.

1203
00:56:23,820 --> 00:56:26,820
The atom by itself,

1204
